    "summary": "The Arameans were a Semitic-speaking people who established numerous city-states across Syria and upper Mesopotamia following the upheavals of the [[event:1815|Bronze Age Collapse]] around 1100 BC. Their principal centers included Damascus, Hamath, Arpad, and Bit Adini along the Euphrates, each functioning as an independent kingdom under its own king while sharing a common language and cultural identity. The Arameans filled the political vacuum left by the collapse of Hittite and Mycenaean power, and their arrival fundamentally reshaped the ethnic and political map of the Levant.\n\nDespite their political fragmentation, the Arameans exercised disproportionate cultural influence through commerce and language. Aramaic, written in an alphabetic script derived from Phoenician, spread as a lingua franca of trade throughout the ancient Near East. By the first millennium BC, Aramaic had become the dominant spoken language from Egypt to Persia, used for diplomacy and administration even by the [[event:61|Assyrian Empire]] that eventually conquered most Aramean kingdoms between the ninth and eighth centuries BC.\n\nThe Aramean city-states maintained their independence through shifting coalitions and alliances against Assyrian expansion. Damascus in particular led repeated coalitions against Assyrian aggression, including an alliance mentioned in Assyrian records as participating in the Battle of Qarqar in 853 BC. The last independent Aramean kingdoms fell to Assyria by 732 BC, but Aramaic language and culture survived and flourished for centuries under Assyrian and later Persian rule.",
